{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480515"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:45:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:45:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"62"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"62","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/62"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.22,0.15,0.12,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"62"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53453"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"62","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/62"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"62"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38919"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1750"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15908"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41975"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53453"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old woman presents with a four-week history of feeling increasingly tired and depressed. She has become constipated and developed urinary frequency and bony pain. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Family history reveals that her mother died of a rare pancreatic cancer six months ago and that her brother has had \u0022trouble with his vision and is being seen by a neurosurgeon\u0022. She is a non-smoker and rarely drinks alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple endocrine neoplasia type 1","Multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2A","Multiple myeloma","Familial hypocalcuric hypercalcaemia","Multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2B"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis woman has features suggestive of hyperparathyroidism. Based of the family history of a possible pancreatic neuro-endocrine neoplasm (mother) and pituitary adenoma (brother), it is very likely this is one of the familial syndromes. \u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple endocrine neoplasia type 1 \u003C/strong\u003E(MEN1) is a rare endocrine tumour syndrome with high penetrance. It primarily causes neoplasia of the parathyroid glands, the anterior pituitary gland, and the neuroendocrine tissue of gastro-entero-pancreatic organ systems.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple endocrine neoplasia type 2A\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with familial medullary thyroid carcinoma (typically seen in early adulthood), with an increased risk for phaeochromocytoma and parathyroid adenoma or hyperplasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple endocrine neoplasia type 2B \u003C/strong\u003Eis associated with medullary carcinoma of the thyroid (typically seen in early childhood) and an increased risk for phaeochromocytoma. Patients with this syndrome have additional features of mucosal neuromas and a marfanoid habitus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is unlikely to have \u003Cstrong\u003Efamilial hypocalcuric hypercalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E as this condition is typically asymptomatic and there is no family history supporting such a diagnosis.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case \u003Cstrong\u003Emultiple myeloma\u003C/strong\u003E is a possible cause of her hypercalcaemia, but is more common in the elderly and unlikely to present in a 44-year-old\u00a0woman.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["MEN1 is a rare, but important cause of hyperparathyroidism."],"references":["Li Y, Simonds WF. Endocrine Neoplasms in Familial Syndromes of Hyperparathyroidism. Endocr Relatability Cancer 2015;23:229-47. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27207564/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38919"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"62"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38919"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-21T16:21:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-21T16:21:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"62"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53453"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relat